\chapter*{ABSTRACT}
    
This project presents a \textbf{FOOD ALLERGY RISK ESTIMATION SYSTEM} designed to assist individuals with food allergies in making safer dietary choices, especially when ingredient information is unavailable. In many real-world scenarios such as restaurants or street food, the exact ingredients of a dish are often unknown, increasing the risk of allergic reactions. Existing solutions primarily rely on food labels or manual ingredient input, which are not effective for mixed or unlabeled foods.

To address this issue, the proposed system utilizes a hybrid approach combining machine learning and rule-based analysis. A custom-built dataset is used to train a lightweight convolutional neural network (MobileNetV2) for food image classification. The system identifies the food item from an uploaded image and estimates possible ingredients based on cuisine and preparation style. These inferred ingredients are then compared with the user’s allergy profile to determine the level of risk.

The system provides a personalized output in the form of risk levels such as Low, Medium, or High, along with explanations to improve user awareness. Although the system does not guarantee medical accuracy, it serves as an effective decision-support tool for early allergy risk detection. This approach reduces dependency on manual input and enhances usability in real-world dining situations

