\chapter{INTRODUCTION}

\section{General Background}
Food allergies are a significant health concern affecting millions of people worldwide. Allergic reactions can range from mild discomfort to severe and life-threatening conditions, making it essential for individuals to be aware of the ingredients present in their food. However, in many real-life situations such as restaurants, street food outlets, or homemade dishes, the exact ingredients are often unknown or not clearly listed. This creates a high risk for individuals with food allergies.

Existing solutions, such as packaged food scanners and allergy-checking applications, mainly depend on labeled ingredients or manual user input. These approaches are not effective for mixed dishes or unlabeled food items, where ingredient details are uncertain. As a result, there is a need for a smarter and more practical solution that can assist users in identifying potential allergy risks without relying entirely on explicit ingredient information.



\section{Objective}
The main objective of this project is to develop a Food Allergy Risk Estimation System that helps users identify potential allergy risks from food items when ingredient details are not available. The system aims to provide an early warning mechanism by analyzing food images and estimating possible ingredients.

The specific objectives include:

\begin{itemize}
\item To identify food items using image-based classification techniques
\item To estimate possible ingredients based on the identified dish
\item To compare inferred ingredients with the user’s allergy profile
\item To provide a clear risk indication as Low, Medium, or High
\item To reduce dependency on manual ingredient input and labeled data
\end{itemize}

\section{Problem Statement}
Food allergies have become a major health concern worldwide, with an increasing number of individuals affected by allergic reactions to common food ingredients such as nuts, dairy, seafood, and gluten. These reactions can vary from mild symptoms to severe conditions like anaphylaxis, making it essential for individuals to be cautious about what they consume. However, ensuring food safety becomes difficult when ingredient information is not readily available.

In real-world scenarios such as restaurants, street food outlets, and homemade meals, food items often contain multiple ingredients that are not explicitly listed or communicated to the consumer. Many dishes are prepared using complex recipes, hidden ingredients, or cross-contamination methods, making it challenging for individuals to accurately identify potential allergens. This uncertainty significantly increases the risk of accidental exposure to harmful substances.

Existing solutions, such as barcode scanners and allergy-checking mobile applications, mainly depend on packaged food labels or require users to manually input ingredients. These approaches are not suitable for mixed or unlabeled foods and often fail to provide accurate or reliable results. Additionally, they lack intelligent decision-making capabilities and do not offer personalized risk assessment based on individual allergy profiles.

Another major challenge is the absence of systems that can interpret food visually and infer possible ingredients. While advancements in machine learning and computer vision have enabled food recognition, their integration into practical allergy risk estimation systems remains limited. There is a clear gap between food identification technologies and real-world allergy safety applications.

Therefore, there is a need for an intelligent and user-friendly system that can analyze food items using image input, estimate possible ingredients, and evaluate potential allergy risks without relying solely on explicit ingredient information. Such a system should provide quick, understandable, and personalized feedback to users, helping them make safer dietary decisions in everyday situations.

\section{Scope}
The scope of this project focuses on the design and development of a web-based Food Allergy Risk Estimation System that assists users in identifying potential allergy risks using food images and personalized allergy data. The system is intended for general awareness and practical use in everyday situations, especially where ingredient information is unavailable or unclear.

The major scope of the system includes:
\begin{itemize}


\item \textbf{Image-Based Food Recognition:}
The system uses a machine learning model (MobileNetV2) to identify food items from images uploaded by the user. This enables automatic detection without requiring manual input.
\item \textbf{Custom Dataset Utilization:}
The model is trained on a custom-built dataset consisting of various food categories, ensuring relevance to real-world and locally available dishes.
\item \textbf{Ingredient Estimation Mechanism:}
Based on the identified dish, the system estimates possible ingredients using predefined rules related to cuisine type and preparation methods.
\item \textbf{Personalized Allergy Profiling:}
Users can input their specific allergies, and the system evaluates food items based on individual sensitivity, making the output personalized.
\item \textbf{Risk Level Prediction:}
The system classifies the allergy risk into three levels — Low, Medium, and High — providing a simple and understandable output for users.
\item \textbf{Explanation-Based Output:}
Along with the risk level, the system provides reasoning or explanation to improve user awareness and trust in the system.
\item \textbf{User-Friendly Web Interface:}
The application is designed with a simple interface using HTML, CSS, and JavaScript, making it accessible to users with minimal technical knowledge.
\item \textbf{Real-Time Processing:}
The system is capable of providing quick results, making it suitable for real-time usage in restaurants or outdoor dining situations.
\item \textbf{Lightweight and Scalable Design:}
The use of MobileNetV2 ensures efficient performance, and the system can be further scaled by expanding the dataset and improving model accuracy.
\end{itemize}

