\chapter{SYSTEM DEVELOPMENT}

\section{Existing system}
Existing systems for food allergy detection mainly rely on traditional methods such as packaged food scanning and manual ingredient input. These systems are commonly available in the form of mobile applications or barcode scanners, which read ingredient labels from packaged food items.

Some applications allow users to manually enter ingredients and check for allergens. However, these approaches are limited in real-world scenarios where food is not labeled, such as restaurant dishes, street food, or homemade meals. Additionally, these systems do not use image-based detection and lack intelligent analysis capabilities.

\subsection{Disadvantages}
\begin{itemize}
    \item Dependence on food labels, which are not available for all food items.
    \item Requires manual entry of ingredients, which is time-consuming.
    \item Not suitable for mixed or complex dishes.
    \item No support for image-based food recognition.
    \item Lack of automation and intelligent decision-making.
    \item Limited personalization based on user allergy profiles.
    \item Inconsistent or unclear risk explanation
\end{itemize}
\newpage
\section{Proposed System}
The proposed system is a Food Allergy Risk Estimation System that uses a combination of machine learning and rule-based logic to provide allergy risk analysis. The system allows users to upload an image of a food item, which is then processed using a lightweight deep learning model (MobileNetV2) to identify the dish.

After identifying the food item, the system estimates possible ingredients based on cuisine and preparation style. These inferred ingredients are then compared with the user’s allergy profile to determine the level of risk. The system provides output in the form of risk levels such as Low, Medium, or High, along with explanations for better understanding.

The proposed system works as a decision-support tool and is designed to be user-friendly, efficient, and suitable for real-world usage where ingredient information is not explicitly available.
\subsection{Advantages}
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Eliminates Dependence on Explicit Ingredient Information:}  The system can estimate allergy risk even when ingredient details are unavailable, making it highly suitable for real-world dining scenarios.
    \item \textbf{Automated Image-Based Food Recognition:} Utilizes a machine learning model (MobileNetV2) to identify food items directly from images, reducing the need for manual input.
    \item \textbf{Personalized Risk Assessment:} Provides customized results by analyzing user-specific allergy profiles, enhancing the relevance and usefulness of the output.
    \item \textbf{Real-Time Risk Evaluation:} Delivers quick and efficient results, making it practical for on-the-spot decision-making in restaurants and outdoor environments.
    \item \textbf{User-Friendly Interface:} Designed with simplicity and       accessibility in mind, allowing users with minimal technical knowledge to  interact with the system.
    \item \textbf{Explainable Output:} Provides clear reasoning along with risk levels, increasing user trust and transparency in system predictions.
    \item \textbf{Reduced Manual Dependency:} Minimizes user effort by automating food identification and risk analysis processes.
    \item \textbf{Scalability and Extensibility:} The system can be enhanced by expanding the dataset, improving model accuracy, and integrating additional features such as real-time ingredient detection.
    \item \textbf{No Login/Signup Required:} For making decisions as fast as possible it will allow to use without sign up or login 
\end{itemize}

\section{Modules}
The system is divided into multiple modules, each responsible for a specific task.

\subsection{User Module}
This module is responsible for collecting and managing user inputs, including food images and allergy preferences. The user uploads a food image through the web interface using options such as drag-and-drop or file browsing, with supported formats including JPG, PNG, and WEBP. The user also selects relevant allergy types from a predefined list. The selected allergy data is stored for future use, enabling personalized allergy risk assessment.

\subsection{Image Preprocessing Module}
This module prepares the uploaded image for analysis by the machine learning model. It performs essential preprocessing operations such as resizing the image to a fixed dimension of 224×224 pixels, which is required for the MobileNetV2 model. 

The module also normalizes pixel values to a range of 0 to 1, improving model performance and stability. Additionally, the image is converted into a numerical array and reshaped into batch format to meet the input requirements of the model. These steps ensure consistency, reduce noise, and enhance the overall accuracy of the classification process.
\subsection{Food Identification Module}
This module is responsible for identifying the food item present in the uploaded image. It uses a trained MobileNetV2 convolutional neural network model, which is optimized for efficient and accurate image classification.

The preprocessed image is fed into the model, which predicts the most probable food category along with a confidence score. The module ensures fast and reliable classification even with limited computational resources. The predicted food label is then forwarded to the next stage for ingredient estimation.
\subsection{Ingredient Estimation Module}
This module estimates the possible ingredients associated with the identified food item. It uses a predefined ingredient database that maps food items to their commonly used ingredients. The module enhances accuracy by considering variations in cuisine and regional preparation styles, allowing it to handle diverse food types. 

The estimated ingredients are structured into a list format, which is then used for further analysis. This module plays a crucial role in bridging the gap between food recognition and allergy detection.
\subsection{Allergy Matching Module}
This module performs the critical task of identifying potential allergens by comparing the estimated ingredients with the user’s selected allergy preferences. It uses a rule-based matching mechanism to detect overlaps between ingredients and known allergenic substances. 

The module generates a list of matched allergens along with the corresponding ingredients responsible for triggering them. This ensures that the system provides accurate and meaningful information about potential risks.
\subsection{Risk Prediction Module}
This module evaluates the severity of the allergy risk based on the results obtained from the allergy matching module. It applies rule-based logic to categorize the risk into predefined levels such as SAFE, MEDIUM, or HIGH. The classification is based on the number and type of detected allergens. The module also generates a clear and concise warning message, helping users understand the level of risk and take appropriate action.
\subsection{Result Display Module}
This module is responsible for presenting the final output to the user in a structured and user-friendly manner. It displays key information such as the identified food name, confidence score, estimated ingredients, and allergy risk level.

Additionally, it highlights detected allergens and provides warning messages for better user awareness. The interface is designed to be intuitive, ensuring that users can quickly interpret the results and make informed decisions.
