\section{System analysis}

The system is analyzed based on its functionality, accuracy, and usability. It effectively identifies food items from images using the trained MobileNetV2 model and estimates allergy risks using rule-based logic. The system is capable of handling real-world scenarios where ingredient information is not available, providing useful decision support to users. The user interface is simple and easy to use, making the system accessible to a wide range of users
\subsection{Testing analysis}
Testing is performed to ensure the correctness and reliability of the system. Different test cases are used, including various food images, allergy combinations, and edge cases such as low-quality or non-food images. The system is verified to produce consistent and meaningful results under different conditions.

\subsection{Unit Testing}
Each module of the system is tested individually to ensure proper functionality. Modules such as image preprocessing, food classification, ingredient estimation, and allergy matching are verified separately. This helps in identifying and fixing errors at an early stage of development..

\subsection{System Testing}
System testing is carried out to evaluate the complete workflow of the application. The system is tested from image upload to result generation to ensure all components are properly integrated and functioning together. This confirms the reliability and stability of the overall system.

\section{Performance Analysis}
The system demonstrates efficient performance with quick response time due to the use of the lightweight MobileNetV2 model. The model achieves an accuracy of 79\%, which is sufficient for a mini project and provides reasonably reliable predictions. The performance of the system depends on factors such as image quality, dataset size, and model training. Although the system provides useful risk estimation, it is not fully accurate and should be considered as a decision-support tool rather than a medical diagnostic system.


